1
00:00:08,214 --> 00:00:09,455
Good evening, everybody.

2
00:00:09,476 --> 00:00:11,819
I messed up yesterday.

3
00:00:11,878 --> 00:00:13,500
Amateur, you see.

4
00:00:14,180 --> 00:00:15,622
So that's the way it is sometimes.

5
00:00:15,702 --> 00:00:16,283
What can you do?

6
00:00:17,304 --> 00:00:18,085
So I shall begin.

7
00:00:20,007 --> 00:00:36,585
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambho Dasa Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Sambha Sambho Dasa

8
00:00:37,966 --> 00:00:50,758
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Harahato Sambha Sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-awakened one.

9
00:00:51,899 --> 00:00:55,862
Even though I wasn't here, I know you all kept to your practice.

10
00:00:56,343 --> 00:00:57,744
There can be no doubt about that.

11
00:00:58,966 --> 00:01:03,070
I have three options, you see, when I go on.

12
00:01:03,090 --> 00:01:05,712
I can go private, which is just for me.

13
00:01:06,147 --> 00:01:11,396
or I can go for only those people whom I've personally invited, or I can go public, you see.

14
00:01:12,177 --> 00:01:13,980
So I made the mistake of going private.

15
00:01:14,000 --> 00:01:15,221
Well, it wasn't so much a mistake.

16
00:01:15,302 --> 00:01:21,371
I thought you'd all be able to beam in because of your extra normal powers, you see.

17
00:01:21,813 --> 00:01:23,394
But I was mistaken.

18
00:01:23,435 --> 00:01:25,938
I had many emails asking me whether I'd died or not.

19
00:01:27,402 --> 00:01:28,022
I haven't died.

20
00:01:29,224 --> 00:01:31,328
So...

21
00:01:31,527 --> 00:01:37,861
What I'm going to do in the evening is try to choose a discourse from the Majjhima Nikaya.

22
00:01:37,960 --> 00:01:38,942
It's a great big book.

23
00:01:41,849 --> 00:01:44,837
There's 160-odd of these discourses.

24
00:01:45,518 --> 00:01:47,602
And just try to make our way through them.

25
00:01:47,963 --> 00:01:50,007
And what I mean to do is...

26
00:01:51,254 --> 00:01:59,704
sort of reduce the discourse to a simple formula and then maybe address some of the things.

27
00:01:59,945 --> 00:02:06,334
Now, you may have questions, questions which are not related to what I'm talking about.

28
00:02:07,234 --> 00:02:14,205
So it's best to email them and I'll answer them that evening if it's before lunch.

29
00:02:15,366 --> 00:02:18,189
Yeah, because after lunch, I'm preparing this, you see.

30
00:02:18,997 --> 00:02:22,401
There were a couple of questions actually that came through.

31
00:02:22,421 --> 00:02:26,288
I haven't put their name, unfortunately.

32
00:02:26,688 --> 00:02:32,858
To what extent can it be argued that the Four Noble Truths was the Buddha's most important teaching?

33
00:02:33,758 --> 00:02:39,868
And then are all the stages of the Eightfold Path equally important?

34
00:02:40,368 --> 00:02:42,532
So I'll tackle that tomorrow, if I may.

35
00:02:42,573 --> 00:02:47,400
And what I'm going to do is chop off the first half hour.

36
00:02:47,902 --> 00:03:04,044
which will be these little discussions or talks, and separate them and list them on the YouTube so you can have a listen to them later if you can't be here for that.

37
00:03:04,064 --> 00:03:04,406
Okay.

38
00:03:07,149 --> 00:03:10,653
So the discourse is called Samaditti.

39
00:03:11,831 --> 00:03:14,235
Sutta, Samadhi discourse.

40
00:03:14,256 --> 00:03:17,700
It means the discourse on right view.

41
00:03:18,080 --> 00:03:21,246
And the person who's giving it isn't the Buddha himself, it's Sariputta.

42
00:03:22,348 --> 00:03:26,252
Now Sariputta was known as the general of the Dharma.

43
00:03:26,272 --> 00:03:30,719
The Buddha gave nicknames to about 80 of his disciples.

44
00:03:31,661 --> 00:03:36,068
So Sariputta was known as Mahapanya, the great wise one.

45
00:03:36,486 --> 00:03:42,693
Moggallana, whom I'm sure you know, was a second sort of disciple, a second great disciple.

46
00:03:43,074 --> 00:03:45,717
He was called Idamantu, which means psychic power.

47
00:03:48,040 --> 00:03:56,550
Some of you will know the story of Bahir of the Barcloth, who asked for instructions while the Buddha was on his arms round.

48
00:03:56,570 --> 00:03:58,032
The Buddha said, can you wait till later?

49
00:03:58,051 --> 00:04:00,175
And he pleaded with him and said, no, I'm an old man.

50
00:04:00,194 --> 00:04:02,176
He's over 73.

51
00:04:02,518 --> 00:04:04,620
And

52
00:04:04,802 --> 00:04:10,688
He gave him this teaching, and he was immediately sort of enlightened, but later on gored by a cow.

53
00:04:11,890 --> 00:04:20,379
And he's known as Kipabinyu, which is the most speediest enlightened person.

54
00:04:20,399 --> 00:04:30,269
There was also Sivali, that's a story that goes with that, which I might say some other time, who was known for his ability just to get arms, even when there was a famine.

55
00:04:30,790 --> 00:04:35,033
So he was called Labi, which just means receiver of gifts.

56
00:04:36,574 --> 00:04:39,918
Two women, two nuns that you may know, are Kisagotami.

57
00:04:41,480 --> 00:04:44,663
She was known as wearing rough robes.

58
00:04:45,343 --> 00:04:52,310
She was the one who had lost a child and was crazed with grief.

59
00:04:52,329 --> 00:04:56,834
And he sent her to find a mustard seed from a house where there'd been no death.

60
00:04:56,995 --> 00:04:58,536
And that brought her back to her senses.

61
00:04:59,122 --> 00:05:02,247
And she ordained and then became fully liberated.

62
00:05:02,629 --> 00:05:08,076
There was also Patachara, which is another terrible story where she lost all her family.

63
00:05:08,117 --> 00:05:14,848
If you remember, the husband on the way back with her husband, her husband died from a snake bite.

64
00:05:14,887 --> 00:05:18,072
The two children were taken away by the great river.

65
00:05:18,553 --> 00:05:24,523
And by the time she got to her village to visit her parents, the house had burnt down with her parents in it.

66
00:05:24,959 --> 00:05:31,267
So she was in a pretty bad state and she also joined the order and became fully liberated.

67
00:05:32,189 --> 00:05:33,831
She was known as Vinaya Dharika.

68
00:05:33,891 --> 00:05:36,495
She was pretty heavy on the old Vinaya, the rule.

69
00:05:38,377 --> 00:05:44,786
The two great lay supporters, Anathapindika, so he was the one who bought the first monastery for the Buddha.

70
00:05:45,908 --> 00:05:47,591
And that's where this actually takes place.

71
00:05:47,651 --> 00:05:52,096
This discourse takes place in Jeta's Grove, Savatthi.

72
00:05:52,668 --> 00:05:58,255
Sarvati was the capital of the Northern Kingdom, whose name I forget.

73
00:05:58,456 --> 00:05:59,437
That's a senior moment.

74
00:06:00,338 --> 00:06:13,896
And he bought this field off Jeta, Prince Jeta, and he said he's covered it with gold, meaning he got done for that, because he wanted the grove so much that Prince Jeta could ask for anything he wanted.

75
00:06:14,598 --> 00:06:17,482
So he's known as Dayaka, which means supporter.

76
00:06:17,502 --> 00:06:20,665
It's a special title that the Buddha gave him.

77
00:06:21,146 --> 00:06:21,206
And

78
00:06:22,233 --> 00:06:29,358
that's a word we use for anybody now who supports the Sangha, the Dayaka.

79
00:06:31,240 --> 00:06:35,625
And, of course, there was Visakha, who was also a very famous supporter of his.

80
00:06:36,605 --> 00:06:48,896
The reason I remember it is because she once turned up at the monastery and all the monks were bathing in the rain, in the torrential monsoon rain, completely naked.

81
00:06:49,057 --> 00:06:50,197
Well, she was very upset.

82
00:06:50,649 --> 00:06:55,274
And so she went out and bought all this cloth so that they could cover themselves.

83
00:06:57,197 --> 00:07:04,305
It never became one of the requisites, one of the eight things that you get when you ordain.

84
00:07:06,326 --> 00:07:09,891
So this is Sariputta who's been asked this question.

85
00:07:09,911 --> 00:07:13,975
And the question is, is there a way?

86
00:07:14,596 --> 00:07:24,709
Is this way the one right view, whose view is straight, who has perfect confidence in the Dharma and has arrived at the true Dharma?

87
00:07:24,769 --> 00:07:35,144
In other words, what do you have to have the right view about, the right understanding about, in order to achieve the right, the true Dharma, the true teachings?

88
00:07:35,706 --> 00:07:37,447
And he gives five ways.

89
00:07:38,608 --> 00:07:44,475
The first one is unwholesome actions and wholesome actions and their roots as to why we behave like that.

90
00:07:45,737 --> 00:07:46,737
Then there's a nutriment.

91
00:07:47,358 --> 00:07:49,420
That's very rarely taught, the nutriment.

92
00:07:51,122 --> 00:07:52,803
And then, of course, there's a Four Noble Truths.

93
00:07:53,704 --> 00:07:56,728
And then he goes through dependent origination backwards.

94
00:07:57,509 --> 00:08:01,072
So he goes from ignorance all the way through to the end.

95
00:08:01,834 --> 00:08:05,798
And then finally, the taints, which, again, some of you might know,

96
00:08:06,250 --> 00:08:13,057
The word is arsua, which is like the sap coming out of a tree, which can make frankincense.

97
00:08:13,117 --> 00:08:14,459
It oozes out of the tree.

98
00:08:15,319 --> 00:08:18,723
But it's also the oozing of pus from a boil.

99
00:08:19,223 --> 00:08:26,050
And I think that's the image we have to have when we think of the arsua that we have to get rid of.

100
00:08:26,110 --> 00:08:36,121
So what I want to do this evening is just talk around about these unwholesome actions.

101
00:08:37,840 --> 00:08:41,504
The list of unwholesome actions, I mean, you know, they're pretty straightforward.

102
00:08:42,265 --> 00:08:43,488
The physical ones, right?

103
00:08:43,967 --> 00:08:45,990
You have to stop killing people, right?

104
00:08:46,572 --> 00:08:48,394
And then you have to stop thieving from them.

105
00:08:49,115 --> 00:08:51,197
And then, of course, there's sexual misconduct.

106
00:08:52,679 --> 00:08:55,524
Now, when it comes, those things are pretty heavy.

107
00:08:55,543 --> 00:08:56,424
They're pretty obvious.

108
00:08:57,447 --> 00:08:59,369
Speech is just a bit more refined.

109
00:08:59,408 --> 00:09:02,734
You've got to be on your guard because we're always speaking.

110
00:09:02,754 --> 00:09:05,738
If we're not speaking to somebody, then we're speaking to ourselves, right?

111
00:09:06,528 --> 00:09:10,032
False speech, you have to stop telling lies from now on, okay?

112
00:09:11,033 --> 00:09:13,976
Malicious speech, that's to do with intent.

113
00:09:15,057 --> 00:09:30,616
Remember, you might say something which, you know, is not giving somebody a good name for, say, a very good reason, but your intention is, you know, to put somebody straight about them if they're employing them, you see.

114
00:09:31,778 --> 00:09:32,458
Something like that.

115
00:09:34,422 --> 00:09:36,484
Then there's abusive speech, right?

116
00:09:37,779 --> 00:09:38,880
abusive speech.

117
00:09:39,621 --> 00:09:45,328
Sometimes it's translated as gossip, but gossip can be more like malicious speech, can't it?

118
00:09:45,809 --> 00:09:47,272
It's more like idle prattle.

119
00:09:47,392 --> 00:09:49,934
That's the best sort of translation.

120
00:09:49,995 --> 00:09:53,119
We're just talking for talking sake.

121
00:09:53,139 --> 00:09:55,201
Now, those are to do with speech.

122
00:09:55,501 --> 00:09:58,424
And so the Buddha is asking us to be guarded with that.

123
00:09:59,606 --> 00:10:05,374
And the mental ones, which are covetousness, wanting what other people have, envy,

124
00:10:05,674 --> 00:10:06,775
At worst, jealousy.

125
00:10:06,797 --> 00:10:08,197
You hate them for having what they have.

126
00:10:09,200 --> 00:10:10,341
And there's ill will, of course.

127
00:10:10,360 --> 00:10:11,081
You don't want any of that.

128
00:10:11,943 --> 00:10:13,926
And, of course, wrong view.

129
00:10:14,647 --> 00:10:15,708
Wrong views about things.

130
00:10:17,029 --> 00:10:20,615
Now, these actions have their roots.

131
00:10:20,936 --> 00:10:24,200
And I'll give you just one second to guess what the roots are.

132
00:10:24,660 --> 00:10:25,542
You won't be surprised.

133
00:10:27,684 --> 00:10:28,586
Yes, you've got it.

134
00:10:29,226 --> 00:10:33,673
It's greed, hatred, or aversion, and delusion.

135
00:10:34,631 --> 00:10:40,499
So this loba dosa moha, loba is really just indulging.

136
00:10:40,739 --> 00:10:42,981
It's just wanting stuff.

137
00:10:43,962 --> 00:10:46,826
It's not a case of I want these days.

138
00:10:46,865 --> 00:10:51,672
It's not a case of I want more TV or more money.

139
00:10:52,192 --> 00:10:54,475
Most people, what we want these days is more.

140
00:10:54,615 --> 00:10:55,657
It becomes a sort of noun.

141
00:10:56,236 --> 00:10:56,878
How much do you want?

142
00:10:56,898 --> 00:10:57,479
You want more.

143
00:10:58,580 --> 00:11:01,803
So that's this business of indulgence.

144
00:11:02,307 --> 00:11:11,456
The aversion, which is a word I prefer, is that you're averse to something and your reaction is either to get rid of it or to get away from it.

145
00:11:11,596 --> 00:11:15,421
So it's the old fight-flight syndrome.

146
00:11:15,441 --> 00:11:24,129
But it's always about manipulating the situation in order to make yourself feel comfortable, most times at the expense of somebody else.

147
00:11:25,812 --> 00:11:28,855
And the delusion, now this digs deep, you see.

148
00:11:29,914 --> 00:11:37,503
because it all begins from this false identity, the false identity of who I am.

149
00:11:38,004 --> 00:11:44,850
So remember, this business of I am me means that I'm seeking my own happiness.

150
00:11:45,851 --> 00:11:47,594
I'm seeking happiness in the world.

151
00:11:48,575 --> 00:11:52,399
And when the world doesn't sort of fit, then, of course, I get this ill will.

152
00:11:53,721 --> 00:11:55,062
And when the

153
00:11:55,260 --> 00:11:58,645
world does fit, you know, it's like me, me, me.

154
00:11:58,666 --> 00:12:01,210
It's all trying to get more and more of what I have.

155
00:12:02,091 --> 00:12:10,004
So it all roots back always to this problem of identity, always roots back to this problem of identity.

156
00:12:10,705 --> 00:12:22,803
And in our practice in Vipassana, we're constantly rediscovering that place within ourselves, which is separating out of these desires and

157
00:12:23,003 --> 00:12:25,505
these ill wills and all the rest of it.

158
00:12:26,587 --> 00:12:33,898
And that's the process of liberating ourselves from this wrong view as to where we can find happiness.

159
00:12:34,578 --> 00:12:38,524
Now, that's not to deny, you know, the natural joys and pleasures of life.

160
00:12:38,604 --> 00:12:42,028
It's just the relationship we have to them.

161
00:12:42,048 --> 00:12:47,817
That relationship is variously called as attachment, indulgence and so on.

162
00:12:48,398 --> 00:12:52,403
And so that's why we end up always trying to manipulate the world, you see.

163
00:12:54,812 --> 00:12:57,115
So it's important to understand that.

164
00:12:57,135 --> 00:13:09,413
Now, one distinction to be made here, which is pretty important, that whenever you read the discourses, it's always about these pretty heavy stuff, you know, like murder and thieving and malicious speech.

165
00:13:10,916 --> 00:13:19,528
And what seems to be missed out, of course, is all the stuff that we generally suffer from in a way, feeling down.

166
00:13:19,548 --> 00:13:21,850
I don't like the word depression.

167
00:13:21,890 --> 00:13:23,113
It sort of medicalizes it.

168
00:13:23,173 --> 00:13:24,094
You just feel down.

169
00:13:24,378 --> 00:13:26,220
I felt down today.

170
00:13:26,500 --> 00:13:26,740
Yes.

171
00:13:27,240 --> 00:13:28,842
So I felt down today.

172
00:13:29,543 --> 00:13:32,166
And and then there's anxiety.

173
00:13:32,407 --> 00:13:33,528
I mean, that's right, isn't it?

174
00:13:33,548 --> 00:13:41,436
Especially now with this coronavirus, the anxiety, the fear that's being generated is quite, quite remarkable.

175
00:13:41,736 --> 00:13:45,139
And rightly so, if it stops people from being silly, you know.

176
00:13:46,741 --> 00:13:46,841
Fear.

177
00:13:48,203 --> 00:13:48,663
Fear.

178
00:13:49,116 --> 00:13:54,143
And then there's an anger, anger which comes up, frustration and all that.

179
00:13:54,503 --> 00:13:56,625
And then you've got all the different hindrances.

180
00:13:57,446 --> 00:14:04,173
So, you know, dullness and lethargy, restlessness, doubt, lots of doubt, things like that.

181
00:14:04,754 --> 00:14:09,500
So now all those come under the umbrella of unwholesomeness.

182
00:14:09,879 --> 00:14:16,827
And so, in a way, a better word than morality, which tends to sink us into this...

183
00:14:17,197 --> 00:14:19,419
You know, thou shalt not and thou shalt.

184
00:14:19,941 --> 00:14:21,081
It's more to do with ethics.

185
00:14:21,142 --> 00:14:25,447
It's more to do with the way we relate to the world.

186
00:14:25,508 --> 00:14:26,950
We relate to people.

187
00:14:27,049 --> 00:14:28,471
That's what it's about.

188
00:14:28,991 --> 00:14:36,522
And everything you have, everything you touch, everything you see, we have a relationship with.

189
00:14:37,192 --> 00:14:40,976
As soon as you see a tree, you find you have a relationship with it, right?

190
00:14:40,996 --> 00:14:41,616
You like it.

191
00:14:42,498 --> 00:14:44,679
You're enjoying its shade and so on.

192
00:14:45,120 --> 00:14:48,663
Even a door, as soon as you see a door, you have a relationship with it.

193
00:14:48,784 --> 00:14:52,168
It's something you want to go through or shut behind you.

194
00:14:52,508 --> 00:14:53,089
It's one of those.

195
00:14:53,809 --> 00:15:04,941
So you can see, to think about karma at its more, at the wider sort of perception of karma, we've got to think about ethics.

196
00:15:06,241 --> 00:15:07,182
That's what it's about.

197
00:15:08,496 --> 00:15:12,761
And of course, what we're trying to do is to get to the opposite of all this.

198
00:15:13,462 --> 00:15:17,988
And of course, that's often stated as non-stealing, et cetera, et cetera.

199
00:15:18,008 --> 00:15:21,312
But of course, what we're moving towards is a refinement.

200
00:15:21,952 --> 00:15:33,746
So once we've stopped killing and we start respecting other people, then you get this idea of protecting them and protecting ourselves, protecting life.

201
00:15:34,466 --> 00:15:36,629
The Buddha's clear that this is a very,

202
00:15:36,947 --> 00:15:40,852
you know, treasured, precious life form that we have.

203
00:15:41,453 --> 00:15:47,883
It has this dual misery and happiness, joy and woe.

204
00:15:47,942 --> 00:15:53,650
But it also has, we have this intelligence, we have this ability to discern.

205
00:15:54,611 --> 00:15:57,836
And that's what's going to liberate us, this ability to discern.

206
00:15:59,238 --> 00:16:04,304
So we need to be very careful with our bodies, right?

207
00:16:07,288 --> 00:16:27,967
When it comes to speech, of course, what we're trying to move towards is a kindly speech, a pure speech, a truthful speech, an ability to speak from the heart, to be open, you know, to be honest.

208
00:16:28,408 --> 00:16:36,216
Those are the sort of important things about right speech.

209
00:16:37,731 --> 00:16:43,441
And the other slightly important thing about that is often to be guarded when you say something.

210
00:16:43,681 --> 00:16:48,589
There's a right time to say something and a right time and a wrong time.

211
00:16:49,029 --> 00:16:57,062
And choosing the wrong time to say something can cause a bit of upset, especially if it's something you want to say that the person might not like.

212
00:16:57,322 --> 00:16:58,524
So you have to be very careful.

213
00:17:00,107 --> 00:17:02,270
I remember when there was all this business of

214
00:17:02,673 --> 00:17:04,153
You know, free speech came up.

215
00:17:04,173 --> 00:17:06,115
It was a while back with Islamists.

216
00:17:06,656 --> 00:17:21,029
And there was this idea that the right to abuse somebody, that was part of this free speech business, which I can understand, but it's a bit of a hard way to put it.

217
00:17:21,971 --> 00:17:32,240
You have a right to state what you understand and believe, even though you know other people might think it might be insulted by it.

218
00:17:32,743 --> 00:17:35,626
but then one has to go very gently with that.

219
00:17:35,727 --> 00:17:44,076
You know, you don't go around sort of smashing people on the head with your views and opinions, you know.

220
00:17:44,096 --> 00:17:46,239
So it's a case of being gentle, kind.

221
00:17:48,080 --> 00:17:49,603
So that's the right speech business.

222
00:17:49,643 --> 00:17:58,232
